# LAB 2.1: TOOL DESCRIPTION QUALITY
# Domain 2 — Task Statement 2.1
# Concept: Five-part description template, keyword overlap, tool splitting
# Time: ~20 minutes | Difficulty: Intermediate
# Prerequisites: Lab 2.2

## Scenario

Your support agent has two tools — `analyze_content` (analyzes web search results) and `analyze_document` (analyzes uploaded PDFs and images). Both descriptions start with "Retrieves and analyzes content from...". The agent picks the wrong one 30% of the time, calling `analyze_content` on PDFs because the descriptions overlap.

You don't need a smarter model. You need tool descriptions that actually distinguish the tools.

## What you'll learn

- Identify why vague tool descriptions cause misrouting in multi-tool agents
- Apply the five-part description template to any tool
- Measure keyword overlap between descriptions as a proxy for routing ambiguity
- Recognize when renaming a tool is not enough -- and splitting is required
- Audit a system prompt for keywords that bias tool selection

## Concepts

Claude selects tools by reading their descriptions and matching them against the current request. When two tools say roughly the same thing -- "Analyzes content and returns results" vs "Analyzes a document and returns results" -- Claude has no signal to prefer one over the other. The result is misrouting: the wrong tool gets called 30% of the time, silently producing incorrect results.

The fix is not a routing classifier. It is not few-shot examples. It is writing descriptions that answer five distinct questions about each tool.

**The five-part template:**

| Part | Question | Example phrase |
|------|----------|----------------|
| **Purpose** | What does this tool do? | "Parses live web search result pages..." |
| **Input format** | What does it expect? | "Input: raw HTML from a search engine results page." |
| **Output format** | What does it return? | "Returns: list of {title, url, snippet, date}." |
| **When to use** | What triggers this tool? | "Use for: search engine results, scraped SERP HTML." |
| **When NOT to use** | What should NOT trigger it? | "Do NOT use for: PDFs, Word documents, invoices." |

The last two parts -- Use for / Do NOT use for -- are the most important. They draw hard boundaries that prevent overlap.

A tool description is a contract, written in advance: it tells Claude exactly when to call this tool and when not to. This is the same pattern as structured error responses (Lab 2.2) -- both reduce ambiguity at the boundary between agent and tool. In Lab 1.7 you saw how a session coordinator routes work to subagents based on their declared capabilities -- tool descriptions serve the same function at the tool level.

