# LAB 2.3: TOOL CHOICE AND SCOPED ACCESS
# Domain 2 — Task Statement 2.3
# Concept: tool_choice modes, scoped tool access, constrained tool replacement
# Time: ~25 minutes | Difficulty: Intermediate
# Prerequisites: Lab 2.2

## Scenario

Your invoice extraction pipeline crashes 15% of the time because `tool_choice: "auto"` returns a text summary instead of calling the extraction tool. Your downstream parser expects structured JSON from a tool call -- when it gets prose, it throws a `KeyError` and the pipeline dies. Meanwhile, your support agent has access to all 18 backend tools, and you're seeing it call `delete_account` when the user just asked a billing question.

You need two fixes: force a tool call when you require structured output (`tool_choice`), and limit which tools each agent can even see (scoped access). A third refinement -- replacing a generic `fetch_url` tool with a domain-restricted `load_document` -- closes the remaining attack surface.

## What you'll learn

- Configuring `tool_choice` modes (`auto`, `any`, forced) to control when Claude must call a tool versus when it may return text
- Why `auto` is unreliable when your downstream system requires structured output
- Restricting each agent role to a scoped tool set (4-5 tools) to prevent cross-specialization misuse
- Replacing generic tools with constrained alternatives that validate inputs at the tool boundary
- Selecting the appropriate combination of tool_choice and scoped access for a given agent role

## Concepts

**Tool choice modes** control whether Claude calls a tool or returns text:

| Mode | Syntax | Behavior | Use when |
|------|--------|----------|----------|
| **auto** | `"auto"` | Claude decides: may return text OR call a tool | Conversational agents where text is fine |
| **any** | `"any"` | Claude MUST call some tool (picks which) | You need structured output but don't care which schema |
| **forced** | `{"type": "tool", "name": "X"}` | Claude MUST call tool X specifically | A specific tool must run first (e.g., extract metadata before enrichment) |

**Scoped tool access** means each agent role gets only the tools relevant to its job. Giving one agent 18 tools increases selection ambiguity -- the model evaluates more candidates, more descriptions overlap, and misrouting multiplies. Scoping to 4-5 tools per role ensures every tool in the set is relevant, matching the principle of least privilege.

**Constrained tool replacement** means swapping a generic tool (e.g., `fetch_url` that accepts any URL) with a domain-restricted version (e.g., `load_document` that only accepts approved document domains). The constraint is enforced at the tool boundary -- unapproved inputs are rejected before execution, not after.

Lab 2.1 designed clear tool descriptions. Lab 2.2 defined structured errors for when tools fail. Lab 2.3 controls which tools an agent sees and how selection happens. All three assume good descriptions -- scoped access and forced selection can't fix tools that Claude can't distinguish.

