## Check your understanding

**Q1.** Your extraction pipeline uses `tool_choice: "auto"`. It works 85% of the time but crashes 15% of the time because Claude returns a text summary instead of calling the extraction tool. What is the correct fix?

**A.** Improve the extraction tool's description so Claude picks it more reliably with `"auto"`
**B.** Set `tool_choice` to `"any"` so Claude must call a tool, guaranteeing structured output
**C.** Add retry logic: if the response is text, re-send the request
**D.** Increase `max_tokens` so Claude has room to return both text and a tool call

**Correct: B.** `"any"` forces a tool call -- Claude must call one of the available tools, eliminating text-only responses that crash the parser. **Why not A:** Better descriptions improve tool selection accuracy but don't eliminate text-only responses -- `"auto"` can always return text regardless of description quality. **Why not C:** Retry is probabilistic -- the second request may also return text, creating a retry loop with no guarantee of success. **Why not D:** `max_tokens` controls output length, not whether Claude calls a tool versus returning text.

---

**Q2.** Your multi-agent system gives all agents access to all 18 backend tools. A customer asks "What's my account balance?" and the support agent calls `delete_account`. Logs show `delete_account` was called on 3 other billing queries this month. What is the root cause and fix?

**A.** The `delete_account` tool description is too vague -- rewrite it using the five-part template
**B.** The support agent's tool set is too broad -- restrict it to the 5 tools relevant to customer support
**C.** Add a `PreToolUse` hook that blocks `delete_account` calls from the support agent
**D.** Remove `delete_account` from the system entirely until the bug is fixed

**Correct: B.** The support agent should never see `delete_account`. Scoping tools to role (4-5 per agent) eliminates the possibility of cross-specialization misuse. **Why not A:** Even a perfectly described `delete_account` tool can be selected when 18 tools compete for attention -- reducing the tool set is the structural fix. **Why not C:** A hook patches one tool but doesn't address the systemic problem -- with 18 tools, other dangerous tools (like `modify_subscription`, `cancel_order`) remain accessible. **Why not D:** Removing the tool entirely breaks admin workflows that legitimately need it.

---

**Q3.** Your research agent uses a generic `fetch_url` tool to retrieve documents. You discover it has been fetching URLs from untrusted domains, including competitor APIs and internal admin endpoints. What is the best fix?

**A.** Add URL validation in the system prompt: "Only fetch from docs.internal.com and arxiv.org"
**B.** Replace `fetch_url` with a constrained `load_document` tool that validates URLs against an approved domain list before fetching
**C.** Add a `PostToolUse` hook that checks the fetched URL and discards results from unapproved domains
**D.** Remove `fetch_url` and have the agent ask the user to provide document content directly

**Correct: B.** A constrained tool validates input before execution -- unapproved URLs are rejected at the tool boundary, never fetched. **Why not A:** Prompt-based URL restrictions have a non-zero failure rate -- the agent may still fetch from unapproved domains despite the instruction. **Why not C:** A `PostToolUse` hook runs after the fetch -- the unapproved URL was already accessed, and any damage (data exfiltration, unauthorized API calls) already happened. **Why not D:** Requiring users to provide content directly eliminates useful automation -- the fix is constraining the tool, not removing it.

## Key takeaways

- `auto`: Claude may return text or call a tool -- unreliable when you need structured output
- `any`: Claude MUST call a tool -- guarantees structured output for downstream parsers
- Forced (`{"type": "tool", "name": "X"}`): Claude MUST call a specific named tool
- Too many tools degrades selection accuracy -- scope to 4-5 per agent role
- Replace generic tools with constrained alternatives that validate inputs at the tool boundary
- These patterns assume good tool descriptions (Lab 2.1) -- scoped access can't fix tools Claude can't distinguish

## Exam tips

- **"Pipeline crashes because model returns text"** --> `tool_choice: "any"` or forced, not better descriptions
- **"Agent has 18 tools and misuses them"** --> scope tools to agent role (4-5 per agent), not "improve all 18 descriptions"
- **Wrong answer trap: "Give full tool access for flexibility"** -- violates principle of least privilege
- **Wrong answer trap: "Add a routing classifier"** -- fix the tool set first before adding infrastructure
- **Constrained replacement vs hooks:** constrained tools reject bad input *before* execution; hooks run *after* the tool already executed
- **The core pattern:** control what tools an agent sees (scoped access) AND when tools are mandatory (tool_choice)

