# LAB 4.1: EXPLICIT CRITERIA TO REDUCE FALSE POSITIVES
# Domain 4 — Task Statement 4.1
# Concept: Specific criteria > vague instructions, false positive impact, trust restoration
# Time: ~20 minutes | Difficulty: Intermediate
# Prerequisites: Lab 3.6

## Scenario

Your code review agent flags 47 issues on a PR. Developers start reading them -- then discover 30 are false positives: TODO comments flagged as "incomplete code," accurate docstrings flagged as "misleading," and idiomatic Python patterns flagged as "code smells." They stop reading after the fifth false positive. The 17 real bugs -- including a SQL injection -- go unnoticed because developers now ignore ALL findings.

The prompt says "review this code and be conservative." But "conservative" means different things each run. You need explicit categorical criteria that define exactly what to report and what to skip.

## What you'll learn

- Writing specific review criteria that define which issues to report (bugs, security) vs skip (style, TODOs)
- Why vague instructions ("be conservative") produce inconsistent results across runs
- The false positive trust spiral: high FP in one category undermines trust in ALL categories
- The two-phase trust restoration strategy: disable high-FP category, fix offline, re-enable
- Building a criteria validator that scores prompts against a false-positive checklist

## Concepts

**Explicit criteria** define exactly what to report and what to skip. "Flag SQL injection and hardcoded credentials. Skip TODO comments, style preferences, and comments that are slightly imprecise but not contradicting actual behavior." This is deterministic -- the model checks specific conditions, not vibes.

**The trust spiral:** When one review category has a 60% false positive rate, developers stop reading ALL findings -- including accurate ones from other categories. The fix is not "improve confidence filtering" (the model is confidently wrong). The fix is **disable the high-FP category immediately** to restore trust, then fix its criteria offline and re-enable.

**Negative examples** ("what NOT to flag") are as important as positive examples. Without them, the model over-reports -- every TODO comment, every imprecise-but-harmless docstring. Lab 2.1 taught that tool descriptions need "Do NOT use for" boundaries. Explicit criteria need the same "Do NOT flag" boundaries.

