# LAB 4.5: BATCH PROCESSING WITH MESSAGE BATCHES API
# Domain 4 -- Task Statement 4.5
# Concept: 50% cost savings, 24hr window, custom_id, blocking vs non-blocking
# Time: ~20 minutes | Difficulty: Intermediate
# Prerequisites: Lab 4.4

## Scenario

Your invoice extraction pipeline processes 10,000 invoices overnight. Running them through the real-time API costs $500/night. Nobody is waiting on the results -- the finance team reviews the extraction report at 9am. The Message Batches API cuts the cost to $250/night (50% discount) and completes within 24 hours.

But your manager also wants to batch the pre-merge security review that blocks every PR. That review needs results in under 5 minutes -- developers are waiting. The Batches API has no latency SLA. You need to know when to batch and when to stay synchronous.

## What you'll learn

- When to use the Message Batches API (non-blocking) vs synchronous API (blocking)
- The 50% cost savings and 24-hour completion window trade-offs
- Using `custom_id` to correlate batch results with source documents and handle per-item failures
- Why multi-turn tool calling is not supported in batch (single request/response only)
- Building a cost calculator that recommends batch vs real-time for a given workload

## Concepts

**The decision rule:** Is anyone waiting on the result right now?
- **Yes** (pre-merge check, customer chat) --> synchronous API
- **No** (overnight report, weekly audit) --> Message Batches API (50% savings)

**Key constraints:**
- **50% cost savings** on all batch requests
- **Up to 24-hour processing window** (usually under 1 hour, but no SLA)
- **No multi-turn tool calling** -- each batch request is a single message/response exchange. You can define tools and get a tool_use response, but you cannot run an agentic loop within a batch request.
- **`custom_id`** is your identifier for each request. Without it, you cannot match results to source documents or resubmit only failed items.

**Failure handling:** When 3 of 100 batch requests fail, identify them by `custom_id`, fix the issue (e.g., chunk oversized documents), and resubmit only the failures -- never the whole batch. Callback to Lab 2.2: batch failures need the same structured error categorization.

**Cost optimization:** Refine prompts on 10-20 synchronous test requests first. Only then submit the full batch. This avoids expensive resubmission of 10,000 requests due to a prompt issue.

