# LAB 4.6: MULTI-INSTANCE AND MULTI-PASS REVIEW
# Domain 4 -- Task Statement 4.6
# Concept: Self-review limits, independent instances, per-file + integration passes
# Time: ~25 minutes | Difficulty: Advanced
# Prerequisites: Lab 4.5

## Scenario

Your code review agent runs once per PR and produces inconsistent results -- the same PR gets different issues flagged on different runs. One run catches SQL injection but misses the missing null check. The next run catches the null check but misses the SQL injection. Single-pass review has variance. For high-stakes reviews (security-critical code, compliance), you need either multi-pass review (run N times, consensus-filter) or multi-instance review (N specialized reviewers, each with a different focus).

Separately, the same Claude session that generates code also reviews it -- and rarely finds bugs. The reasoning context from generation makes it blind to its own mistakes.

## What you'll learn

- Why self-review fails (reasoning context creates attachment to original decisions)
- Multi-pass consensus: run N times, report issues found in 2+ of N passes
- Multi-instance specialization: distinct focus per reviewer (security, performance, style)
- Per-file local analysis + cross-file integration pass for large PRs (Lab 1.6 callback)
- The trade-off: consensus filtering can hide real bugs found by only one pass

## Concepts

**Self-review limitation:** When the same session generates and reviews code, the model retains its reasoning context. The decisions that led to the code still feel "correct" -- the model defends its choices instead of questioning them. An independent instance with no prior context catches more issues.

**Multi-pass consensus (2-of-3, 3-of-5):** Run the review N times and report only findings that appear in 2+ passes. This reduces variance (random false positives drop out) but has a cost: a real bug found by only one pass gets filtered. Consensus is conservative.

**Multi-instance specialization:** Instead of N copies of the same review, use N specialized reviewers -- one for security, one for performance, one for style. Each has a focused prompt and criteria. Coverage is broader because each reviewer has a distinct lens.

**Per-file + cross-file (Lab 1.6 callback):** For large PRs (10+ files), split into per-file local analysis passes + a separate cross-file integration pass. Single-pass review of 12 files causes attention dilution -- detailed feedback on the first 3, shallow on the rest.

